						<summary>

						<p>Slab setup on the hude.</p>						

						<p><hi rend="bold">Tribhuvanamalla [Vikramāditya VI]. 11th century A.D.</hi></p>						

						<p>The slab is broken into two pieces from top to bottom and the left portion piece is lost. On the basis of the information obtained from the right portion piece it can be said that it is a Kalyāṇi Chālukya record belonging to about the 11th century A.D. The king was ruling from [Kalyā]ṇada nelevīḍu. It mentions Tuppadūra prabhu [probably a subordinate ruler] and the installation of a god [name lost] at the place <hi rend="italic">[a]grahāra</hi> [name lost] and records the grant of 400 <hi rend="italic">kamma</hi> land-garden for the worship and offerings to the god.</p>						

						<p>There is a mention of god Māṇikēśvara. Perhaps it was this god installed [in the newly built temple] and the grant of land belong to this temple.</p>						

						<p>In the date portion only [Chālukya] Vikrama year, śu. 3, Thursday can be made out which is insufficient for verification. [Yet, it can be suggested here that the record belongs to the reign period of Chālukya Vikramāditya VI].</p>						

						</summary>
					</msContents>
